<TITLE> Iran police detain six student activists </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TEHRAN, July 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iranian police detained six student activists on Monday after they held a sit-in in front of a Tehran university to mark the anniversary of student unrest in 1999, a police spokesman was quoted as saying. Authorities had banned gatherings to mark the day eight years ago when hardline vigilantes attacked a Tehran University dormitory, killing one person and sparking five days of protests and some of the worst unrest in Iran since the 1979 revolution. "The six activists were arrested this morning after the sit-in that took place in front of the Amir Kabir university," said Police General Mehdi Ahmadi, students news agency ISNA reported. ISNA said the official did not say why the students were arrested and said it was not clear where they were being held. Witnesses said they saw police around the Tehran University compound, apparently positioned to disperse any possible anniversary gatherings. Rights activists and Western diplomats say pro-reform students have been among groups targeted in what they say is a fresh crackdown on dissenting voices. Others being pressured include labour movement figures and intellectuals, they say. Security forces arrested nine people after attacking a meeting of Iran's largest student group, the pro-reform Office to Consolidate Unity (OCU), a student activist told Reuters. "Plainclothes men attacked the meeting, which was held to discuss the students' arrest after the sit-in," said activist Farid Modaresi. That report could not be confirmed independently. Iran's pro-democracy students have paid a heavy price in recent years and most of their leaders have fled the country or have been put in jail by the clerical establishme
